{{Use British English|date=December 2011}} {{Use dmy dates|date=December 2011}} {{Infobox recurring event | name = Global Peace and Unity | native_name = | native_name_lang = | logo = | logo_caption = | image = | imagesize = | caption = | status = Active | genre = Conference | dates = Third week of an Autumn month | begins = Saturday | ends = Sunday | frequency = | venue = [[ExCeL London|ExCeL Exhibition Centre]] | location = [[Royal Victoria Dock]], [[London]], [[England]] | coordinates = | country = [[United Kingdom]] | years_active = 2005–present | first = 2005 | last = 2013 | prev = | next = | participants = | attendance = Over 50,000 | area = | budget = | activity = | patron = | organised = [[Islam Channel]] | filing = | people = | member = | website = {{URL|http://www.theglobalunity.com/}} | footnotes = }}
The '''Global Peace and Unity''' event/festival (often abbreviated as '''GPU''') is a recurring two-day conference held at the [[ExCeL London|ExCeL Exhibition Centre]] in [[Royal Victoria Dock]], [[London]], [[England]] and organized by the [[Islam Channel]]. It is the largest [[Muslim]], [[Interfaith dialog|interfaith]] and [[Multiculturalism|multicultural]] event of its kind in [[Europe]], having attracted over 55,000 visitors from five continents during the 2006 event.<ref name="guardian1">{{cite news |last=Safdar|first=Anealla| url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2006/dec/04/mondaymediasection1|title=The untold good news story about Muslims|work=Dispatches|location= |publisher=''[[The Guardian]]''|date=4 December 2006|accessdate=28 October 2007}}</ref> There have been six conferences since its inception in the inaugural event held on 4 December 2005, with others in 2006, 2007, 2008, 2010 and 2013. The conference includes an Islamic exhibition, an evening [[Anasheed|nasheed]] concert, as well as a series of talks, workshops, seminars and lectures from international speakers spanning the two days.<ref name="guardian1"/><ref name="GPU07">{{cite web |url=http://www.theglobalunity.com/|title=Global Peace & Unity Event 2007 - 24th & 25th November 2007|accessdate=27 October 2007}}</ref>
==Purpose== According to the official website, the Global Peace and Unity event is designed to promote "global cohesion across all communities," as well as "break barriers and build bridges between the variety of cultures and groups that follow the Islamic faith."<ref name="GPU07"/> As well as giving Muslims the opportunity to enjoy themselves and provide a platform for them to learn more about their religion.<ref>[[Islam Channel]], The Global Peace & Unity Event 2005 Special Collector's Edition DVD</ref> The event aspires to spread peace and foster unity between like-minded representatives of communities in the UK and worldwide. It aims to bring together people from all spheres of the British society in order to inform and educate them about Islam and Muslims, and through this help to bridge the gaps between Muslims and non-Muslims and improve community relations.<ref name="guardian1"/><ref name="objectives">{{cite web |url=http://www.theglobalunity.com/10/info/media/origin-and-values-menu|title=Global Peace & Unity Event - Origin and Values|accessdate=1 January 2011}}</ref>
According to Khurram Mujtaba, director of operations of Islam Channel, "the event is a means through which to promote dialogue."<ref name="guardian1"/> According to [[Mohamed Ali Harrath]], chairman of the event and Islam Channel’s CEO, "the event offers a crucial platform for demanding change through peaceful interfaith dialogue, and positive exchange of ideas and interaction towards fostering mutual understanding between people from every culture, faith and background in a bid for greater community cohesion in a multicultural society."<ref name="ethnicnow">{{cite web |url=http://www.ethnicnow.com/channels/arts-culture/press-release/5/861/the-global-peace-and-unity-event.html|title=Ethnic Now - The Global Peace and Unity Event 2006|accessdate=22 November 2006}}</ref><ref name="chairman">{{cite news |last=Ali|first=Mohamed |url=http://www.theglobalunity.com/10/info/media/message-from-chairman-menu|title=Message From Global Peace and Unity Event Chairman Ali|work= |location= |publisher=[[Islam Channel]]|date=22 October 2010|accessdate=29 August 2011}}</ref>
==Features== The event consists of three main parts. One is an exhibition which houses numerous stalls, selling Islamic gifts and serving cuisines emanating from a variety of cultures. Other stalls promote Islamic business, while yet others are reserved for the collection of [[Charity (practice)|charity]] donations for organizations like [[Muslim Aid]] and [[Islamic Relief]]. The other two parts of the event are composed of an evening concert on the first day and series of talks and lectures by international speakers on the second. Throughout both days artists provide entertainment on-stage in the form of nasheed pieces or comedy sketches.<ref name="guardian1"/><ref name="chairman"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Mayet|first=Fahad|url=http://www.islamonline.net/servlet/Satellite?c=Article_C&cid=1165994313617&pagename=Zone-English-Youth/YTELayout|title=Global Peace and Unity Event, London|work=|location=|publisher=[[IslamOnline]]|date=21 December 2006|accessdate=27 October 2007|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070316193805/http://www.islamonline.net/servlet/Satellite?c=Article_C&cid=1165994313617&pagename=Zone-English-Youth%2FYTELayout|archivedate=16 March 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
==Speakers, artists and performers== Numerous individuals have spoken at the Global Peace and Unity event, including political figures and community leaders such as former (and then serving) London mayor [[Ken Livingstone]], [[Respect Party|Respect]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] [[George Galloway]]; former [[Muslim Council of Britain|MCB]] Secretary-Generals [[Iqbal Sacranie]] and [[Muhammad Abdul Bari]]; journalists [[Yvonne Ridley]] and [[Sarah Joseph (editor)|Sarah Joseph]]; politicians such as [[Nazir Ahmed, Baron Ahmed|Lord Nazir Ahmed]], [[Charles Falconer, Baron Falconer of Thoroton|Lord Charles Falconer]], [[Salma Yaqoob]], [[Simon Hughes|Simon Hughes MP]], [[Sadiq Khan|Sadiq Khan MP]], [[Stephen Timms|Stephen Timms MP]] and [[Shahid Malik|Shahid Malik MP]]; political activist [[John Rees (activist)|John Rees]], entrepreneur [[James Caan (entrepreneur)|James Caan]]; ex-sportsmen [[Saeed Anwar]] and [[Imran Khan]].<ref name="times">{{cite news |last=Bale|first=Joanna| url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article745910.ece|title=Muslim peace rally attracts thousands| work= |location=London |publisher=[[The Times]]|date=5 December 2005|accessdate=27 October 2007}}</ref><ref name="GPU05">{{cite web|url=http://www.moftak.com/gu05/|title=Global Peace & Unity Event 2005 - 4th December 2005|accessdate=27 October 2007|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071030045917/http://www.moftak.com/gu05/|archivedate=30 October 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name="GPU06">{{cite web|url=http://www.moftak.com/gu06/|title=Global Peace & Unity Event - 25th & 26th November 2006|accessdate=27 October 2007|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071110203659/http://www.moftak.com/gu06/|archivedate=10 November 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name="GPU08">{{cite web |url=http://www.theglobalunity.com/08/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=72&Itemid=46|title=Global Peace & Unity Event 2008 - 25th & 26th October 2008|accessdate=29 August 2011}}</ref><ref name="GPU10">{{cite web |url=http://www.theglobalunity.com/10/conference/speakers|title=Global Peace & Unity Event 2010 - 23rd & 24th October 2010|accessdate=1 January 2011}}</ref>
Islamic scholars and preachers who have spoken at the Global Peace and Unity event have included [[Zakir Naik]], [[Abu Ammaar Yasir Qadhi|Yasir Qadhi]], [[Yusuf Estes]], [[Jamal Badawi]], [[Timothy Winter]], [[Joel Hayward]], [[Abdul Wahid Pedersen]], [[Muhammad Tahir-ul-Qadri]], [[Muhammad al-Yaqoubi]] and [[Tariq Ramadan]]. Representatives from other faiths including [[Yisroel Dovid Weiss]] and [[Riah Abu El-Assal]].<ref name="guardian1"/><ref name="ethnicnow" /><ref name="GPU06" /><ref name="GPU08" /><ref name="GPU10" />
Muslim pop singers who have performed at the Global Peace and Unity event include [[Jermaine Jackson]] and [[Yusuf Islam]]. Nasheed artists to have performed include [[Zain Bhikha]], [[Ahmed Bukhatir]], [[Junaid Jamshed]], [[Najam Sheraz]], [[Dawud Wharnsby|Dawud Wharnsby Ali]], [[Idris Phillips]], [[Native Deen]] and [[Outlandish]]. Other performers have included poet [[Brother Dash]]; comedians [[Preacher Moss]], [[Azhar Usman]] and [[Baba Ali]].<ref name="GPU05" /><ref name="GPU06"/><ref name="GPU08" />
==Controversy== In 2010, [[David Cameron]] banned [[Sayeeda Warsi, Baroness Warsi|Baroness Sayeeda Warsi]] from attending the conference over alleged extremist speakers.<ref name="guardian2">{{cite news |last=Townsend|first=Mark|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/oct/24/baroness-warsi-islamic-conference-ban|title=Baroness Warsi told by David Cameron not to appear at Islamic conference|work= |location= |publisher=''[[The Guardian]]''|date=24 October 2010|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref><ref name="telegraph1">{{cite news |last=Collins|first=Nick|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/8084340/Baroness-Warsi-pulls-out-of-Muslim-conference-amid-claims-of-Tory-concerns.html|title=Baroness Warsi pulls out of Muslim conference amid claims of Tory concerns|work= |location= |publisher=''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''|date=25 October 2010|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref><ref name="hindustantimes">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/u-k-pm-bans-baroness-warsi-from-attending-islamic-conference/article1-617160.aspx|title=U.K. PM bans Baroness Warsi from attending Islamic conference|work= |location=India|publisher=''[[Hindustan Times]]''|date=24 October 2010|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref> Speakers have included: Former Pakistani government minister, [[Muhammad Ijaz-ul-Haq]], who said suicide attacks were a justified response to [[Salman Rushdie]]'s 2007 knighthood. Shady al-Suleiman, who invited [[Anwar al-Awlaki]] to speak at a mosque in Australia and supports stoning adulterers. Abdur Rashid Turabi, head of Pakistan's [[Jamaat-e-Islami]] party. Sheikh [[Abu Ammaar Yasir Qadhi|Yasir Qadhi]], who said that homosexuality is an "aberration against God".<ref name="guardian2"/> [[Hussein Ye]], who blamed Jews for the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref name="telegraph2">{{cite news |last=Gillgan|first=Andrew|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/journalists/andrew-gilligan/7908262/Hizb-ut-Tahrir-is-not-a-gateway-to-terrorism-claims-Whitehall-report.html|title=Hizb ut Tahrir is not a gateway to terrorism, claims Whitehall report|work= |location= |publisher=''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''|date=25 July 2010|accessdate=29 June 2015}}</ref> <ref name="telegraph3">{{cite news |last=Gillgan|first=Andrew|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/terrorism-in-the-uk/11367966/The-rising-tide-of-anti-Semitism.html|title=The rising tide of anti-Semitism|work= |location= |publisher=''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''|date=25 January 2010|accessdate=29 June 2015}}</ref>
